            <h2>Dog Care</h2>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Provide Proper Nutrition</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Feed your dog high-quality commercial dog food or a balanced homemade diet as recommended by your veterinarian.</li>
                        <li>Follow feeding guidelines based on your dog’s age, size, and activity level.</li>
                        <li>Ensure your dog has access to fresh, clean water at all times.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Regular Exercise</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Take your dog for daily walks to ensure they get enough exercise.</li>
                        <li>Engage in play activities like fetch, tug-of-war, and interactive toys to keep your dog physically and mentally stimulated.</li>
                        <li>Allow your dog to interact with other dogs and people to develop good social behavior.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Veterinary Care</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Schedule regular vet visits for health checkups and vaccinations.</li>
                        <li>Administer flea, tick, and heartworm preventives as recommended by your vet.</li>
                        <li>Consider spaying or neutering your dog to prevent unwanted litters and reduce certain health risks.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Grooming</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Brush your dog’s coat regularly to prevent matting and reduce shedding.</li>
                        <li>Bathe your dog as needed using a dog-specific shampoo.</li>
                        <li>Trim your dog’s nails regularly to prevent overgrowth and discomfort.</li>
                        <li>Check and clean your dog’s ears regularly to prevent infections.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Training and Discipline</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Teach your dog basic commands like sit, stay, come, and heel.</li>
                        <li>Train your dog to eliminate outside or in designated areas.</li>
                        <li>Use positive reinforcement techniques like treats and praise to encourage good behavior.</li>
                        <li>Be consistent with rules and training to avoid confusion and reinforce good behavior.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Mental Stimulation</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Provide toys that challenge your dog’s mind, such as puzzle toys and treat-dispensing toys.</li>
                        <li>Engage in training games that require your dog to think and problem-solve.</li>
                        <li>Expose your dog to new environments, smells, and activities to keep them mentally sharp.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Safe Environment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ensure your yard is securely fenced to prevent your dog from escaping.</li>
                        <li>Provide a comfortable and safe space for your dog to rest and sleep.</li>
                        <li>Keep harmful substances like chemicals, certain plants, and human foods out of reach.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Love and Attention</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Spend quality time with your dog, showing them love and affection.</li>
                        <li>Provide comfort and care when your dog is feeling anxious or unwell.</li>
                        <li>Pay attention to changes in your dog’s behavior or health and seek veterinary care if needed.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>
